## 2. Coding the Nexus Mask in the Script\
To achieve this without manual editing, your automated looping tool needs a conditional rule for the Nexus phase. Instead of a temporal crossfade (xfade over time), it executes a **spatial wipe mask** fixed at the 50% horizontal mark of the video frame.\
Here is the FFmpeg pipeline logic to bake this specific layout:\
```python\
def generate_nexus_collision(clip_counting_up, clip_counting_down, output_path):\
    """\
    Spatially splits the 16:9 frame down the center.\
    Left half runs the beginning of the loop sequence.\
    Right half runs the collapsing end of the loop sequence.\
    """\
    input_up = ffmpeg.input(clip_counting_up)\
    input_down = ffmpeg.input(clip_counting_down)\
    \
    # 1. Crop the left half of the Up timeline (0 to width/2)\
    left_half = input_up.video.filter('crop', w='iw/2', h='ih', x=0, y=0)\
    \
    # 2. Crop the right half of the Down timeline (width/2 to width)\
    right_half = input_down.video.filter('crop', w='iw/2', h='ih', x='iw', y=0)\
    \
    # 3. Stack them horizontally side-by-side to create the unified 16:9 frame\
    nexus_video = ffmpeg.filter([left_half, right_half], 'hstack')\
    \
    # 4. Audio Chaos: Mix the past and future audio stems, hard panning them\
    audio_up = input_up.audio.filter('pan', 'stereo|c0=c0|c1=0')    # Hard Left\
    audio_down = input_down.audio.filter('pan', 'stereo|c0=0|c1=c1') # Hard Right\
    nexus_audio = ffmpeg.filter([audio_up, audio_down], 'amix', inputs=2)\
    \
    # Compile the Nexus asset\
    output = ffmpeg.output(nexus_video, nexus_audio, output_path, vcodec='libx264', acodec='aac')\
    output.run(overwrite_output=True, quiet=True)\
    \
    print(f"[\uc0\u55357 \u56485 ] NEXUS COLLISION COMPILED: \{output_path\}")\
\
```\
